The offsite consequence analysis for the Water Treatment Plant includes consideration of two release scenarios for each parameter of concern (chlorine): 

1. A Worst-Case Release
2. An Alternative Scenario

The following key elements outline the accidental release prevention program for the Weslaco Water Treatment Plant:
$	High level of training of the operators;
$	Preventive maintenance program;
$	Use of state of the art process and safety equipment;
$	Use of accurate and effective operating procedures, written with the participation of the operators;
$	Performance of a hazard review of equipment and procedures;
$	Implementation of an audit and inspection program.

The facility has a Hot Work Permit procedure, a procedure for contractors working at the plant, an employee participation plan, and a Management of Change procedure. The facility also has a written Employee Participation Plan. Employees participate in the Process Hazard Analysis and have access to their training records and other information.

Chemical-specific prevention steps include operator use of available Self-Contained-Breathing-Apparatus (SCBA) during connection/disconnection of the chemical supply, awareness of the hazardous and toxic properties of chlorine and the presence of a chemical detector.  An Agreement with Chemical Response & Remediation Contractors, Inc.(CRRC) has been made for assistance with emergency response.

No accidental releases of chlorine have occurred at the site in the past five years.
